Heart Disease Prediction

¶

The World Health Organization (WHO) estimates that 17.9 million people die from cardiovascular diseases (CVDs) every year.

There are multiple risk factors that could contribute to CVD in an individual, such as unhealthy diet, lack of physical activity, or mental illness. Identifying these risk factors early on could help prevent many premature deaths.

We are working for an R&D company that focuses on providing healthcare solutions. The company has collected anonymized data from multiple hospitals on several patients. The dataset includes relevant information for each patient, such as their personal information and some medical data, including whether or not they have had heart disease before.

We are tasked with using the dataset to accurately predict the likelihood of a new patient having heart disease in the future.

The dataset has the following features:

Feature Description
Age age of the patient [years]
Sex sex of the patient [M: Male, F: Female]
ChestPainType chest pain type [TA: Typical Angina, ATA: Atypical Angina, NAP: Non-Anginal Pain, ASY: Asymptomatic]
RestingBP resting blood pressure [mm Hg]
Cholesterol serum cholesterol [mm/dl]
FastingBS fasting blood sugar [1: if FastingBS > 120 mg/dl, 0: otherwise]
RestingECG resting electrocardiogram results [Normal: Normal, ST: having ST-T wave abnormality (T wave inversions and/or ST elevation or depression of > 0.05 mV), LVH: showing probable or definite left ventricular hypertrophy by Estes' criteria]
MaxHR maximum heart rate achieved [Numeric value between 60 and 202]
ExerciseAngina exercise-induced angina [Y: Yes, N: No]
Oldpeak oldpeak = ST [Numeric value measured in depression]
ST_Slope the slope of the peak exercise ST segment [Up: upsloping, Flat: flat, Down: downsloping]
HeartDisease output class [1: heart disease, 0: Normal]

We have 918 observations, 11 features and 1 target column. There are no missing values in the dataset. Mean age is 53.

Numeric Features (Continuous Variables):
If there is no possible intermediate value between any two adjacent values of a variable, we call that variable discrete. In our dataset 'Age', 'RestingBP', 'Cholestrol' and 'MaxHR' are reported as integers (rounded off) but these are actually measured with fractional precision and treated as continuous in statistical and medical contexts. So we will be treating these as continuous variable for the purpose of our analysis. 'Oldpeak' is a continuous variable and is already of type float.

Categorical Features (Discrete Variables):
Following are categorical features: 'Sex','ChestPainType','FastingBS','RestingECG','ExerciseAngina','ST_Slope'

So we have 5 numeric features and 6 categorical features. We will be one-hot encoding categorical features. 'FastingBS' doesn't need one hot encoding because it already has binary values 0 and 1.

Target:
Target variable 'HeartDisease' does not need label encoding because it already has binary values 0 and 1.

We have 1 observation where RestingBP is 0 and 172 observations where Cholesterol is 0. This requires careful handling, as a cholesterol level of 0 is physiologically implausible and likely indicates missing or erroneous data. The most effective approach involves imputing these zero values using context-aware methods rather than simply removing or replacing them with a global statistic.

We have 79% Males and 21% Females in the dataset. This imbalance in the dataset can cause problems when building a predictive model. Machine learning models trained on such imbalanced data may become biased toward the majority group (males), leading to reduced accuracy and fairness in predicting heart disease for females. Models can have higher performance on male patients due to overrepresentation, while female-specific patterns may be underlearned, resulting in disparities in prediction outcomes.

To mitigate this we will assess model performance separately for males and females to ensure equitable predictions.

Above plots show that ChestPainType 'ASY' (Asymptomatic) has higher count for patients with heart disease. This reflects a well-documented clinical phenomenon: many individuals with heart disease do not experience chest pain. This is particularly common in high-risk groups such as diabetics, the elderly, and women. This underscores the need for models to rely on multiple predictors—not just symptoms—for accurate risk assessment.

79.4% of patients with FastingBS =1 (blood sugar greater than 120 mg/dl) are diagnosed with heart disease in relation to those who were not. This means among patients with elevated blood sugar, a high proportion were diagnosed with heart disease. This reflects a strong association between hyperglycemia and heart disease.However, this does not imply causation — it indicates that high fasting glucose is a significant risk marker in the cohort we got. This percentage is likely inflated compared to general population rates because Fasting blood sugar ≥ 120 mg/dL (≈6.7 mmol/L) indicates diabetes, and while it increases the risk of heart disease, it does not mean nearly 80% of such patients have heart disease. So this insight should be used to flag high-risk patients, but models should not assume all such individuals have heart disease without considering other factors.

Imputation of erroneous data

¶

There are a few ways we can handle these values:

  1. We could remove those rows entirely if their frequency of occurrence were low. But that is not the case for 'Cholesterol' feature.
  2. One good strategy is to replace the zero cholesterol values with the median cholesterol value specific to the group of patients who have the same heart disease status (i.e., those with and without heart disease). This method preserves potential relationships between cholesterol levels and heart disease, as it accounts for the underlying distribution within each subgroup, thereby reducing bias in the model.
  3. We could try some complex approaches. For example, instead of using the median of the entire column, maybe we could look at the median of the values grouped by the age, sex, and/or resting ECG of the patient. The resting blood pressure of a female in her 30s with a normal ECG might be lower than what we would get from the median of the entire column.

The third option might give us a slightly more accurate result, but given the small size of our dataset, we can ignore it for now and use the 2nd strategy.

We can do a similar step for the single observation where RestingBP is 0.

Back to the top

In [21]:
df_imputed = copy.deepcopy(df)
# Replace 0s with NaN temporarily, then fill by group median
df_imputed['Cholesterol'] = df_imputed['Cholesterol'].replace(0, np.nan)
df_imputed['Cholesterol'] = df_imputed.groupby('HeartDisease')['Cholesterol'].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))

# Replace 0s with NaN temporarily, then fill by group median
df_imputed['RestingBP'] = df_imputed['RestingBP'].replace(0, np.nan)
df_imputed['RestingBP'] = df_imputed.groupby('HeartDisease')['RestingBP'].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))

Stratified Train Test Split

¶

Let's split the data into train and test sets first before any feature selection steps to prevent data leakage. This ensures no information from the test set leaks into the training process, and transformations are consistent and reproducible.

Data is highly imbalanced based on 'Sex', so will stratify the train test split on both 'HeartDisease' and 'Sex' to preserve the distribution of combined categories.

(Note: stratify doesn't work after one hot encoding, so we need to split before we one hot encode categorical columns)

We have used mutual information and visualization to determine top 10 features. Let's use KNN algorithm, fit the model using one of these features at a time, then compare and see which features are strongest predictors.

We will use f1_score as the scoring metric because it balances precision and recall. In medical diagnosis, the goal is to maximize the True Positive Rate and minimize the False Negative Rate. This means we need to have high recall.

In [36]:
f1_scores = {}
for feature in top_10_features:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5,p=2,weights='uniform')
    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=4, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
    scores = cross_val_score(knn,X_train_encoded[[feature]],y_train,scoring='f1',cv=cv)
    f1_scores[feature] = scores.mean()
f1_scores

We see poor F1 score when using only the Sex feature and in an imbalanced dataset it is expected. Since the dataset has a strong imbalance in the Sex feature (fewer females), and heart disease prevalence may differ by sex, a model trained solely on this feature struggles to achieve good precision and recall—especially for the minority class (females). The F1 score, being the harmonic mean of precision and recall, will be low if either is poor.

In imbalanced settings, the model may overwhelmingly predict the majority class (male), leading to:

  • High accuracy for males,
  • Poor recall for females (many false negatives),
  • Low overall F1 score due to imbalance and lack of discriminative power.

This reflects both the limited predictive capacity of a single binary feature and the bias introduced by class imbalance.

Conclusion

¶

Best parameters found by grid search for KNeighborsClassifier are:

{'metric': 'manhattan', 'n_neighbors': 7, 'weights': 'uniform'})

We have a fitted this model to the test data and achieved 0.87 f1_score overall. But as expected, due to imbalance in the dataset for Sex feature, model has poor recall of 0.7 for females compared ot 0.9 for males. The goal is equitable performance across genders. For this reason, our model is not ready to be used in real-world healthcare setting.

For further improvement of this model we can consider following options:

  1. Apply class weighting during training to penalize misclassification of females more heavily.
  2. Use SMOTE or other oversampling techniques to balance the representation of females in the training data.
  3. Adjust classification thresholds—lower the threshold for predicting heart disease in females to increase sensitivity.
  4. Adopt fairness-aware modeling, such as individualized probability thresholds by sex, which has been shown to improve F1 scores and recall.
